00:00:52,586 --> 00:00:55,387
   narrator: when luring fish   
   to a hole in a frozen lake,  

4
00:00:55,389 --> 00:00:58,324
        it helps to take        
       a crafty approach.       

5
00:00:58,326 --> 00:01:00,726
       it's a handcrafted       
       piece of folk art,       

6
00:01:00,728 --> 00:01:02,995
          and it's also         
    a cunning piece of work.    

7
00:01:02,997 --> 00:01:05,197
     often brightly colored     
       with bold patterns,      

8
00:01:05,199 --> 00:01:07,399
       the decoy attracts       
    the attention of fish --    

9
00:01:07,401 --> 00:01:11,504
          an attraction         
  that will likely prove fatal. 

10
00:01:14,208 --> 00:01:16,208
     native north americans     

11
00:01:16,210 --> 00:01:18,677
  were the first to use decoys  
  to catch fish in the winter.  

12
00:01:18,679 --> 00:01:22,214
        european settlers       
     followed their example.    

13
00:01:22,216 --> 00:01:23,549
      and centuries later,      

14
00:01:23,551 --> 00:01:27,153
     decoy artists carry on     
   this tradition of trickery.  

15
00:01:27,155 --> 00:01:28,487
        at this workshop,       

16
00:01:28,489 --> 00:01:31,691
        the decoy starts        
  with a plank of white cedar.  

17
00:01:31,693 --> 00:01:35,761
 it's a wood with dense fibers, 
  so it won't expand when wet.  

18
00:01:35,763 --> 00:01:39,297
   he draws a basic fish shape  
     on the wood freestyle.     

19
00:01:39,299 --> 00:01:43,301
            this one            
    is to resemble a herring.   

20
00:01:43,303 --> 00:01:45,371
     he carves out the shape    
        with a band saw,        

21
00:01:45,373 --> 00:01:47,106
      producing the blank,      

22
00:01:47,108 --> 00:01:50,509
  which can now be transformed  
       into a fish decoy.       

23
00:01:54,048 --> 00:01:58,484
      he cuts a narrow slot     
 for attaching a metal tail fin.

24
00:02:02,190 --> 00:02:05,758
     he draws a center line     
     around the decoy blank.    

25
00:02:07,395 --> 00:02:09,128
this serves as a reference point

26
00:02:09,130 --> 00:02:12,465
   as he now tapers the edges   
       with a sharp knife.      

27
00:02:12,467 --> 00:02:16,869
      if he cuts too deep,      
   he could spoil the carving,  

28
00:02:16,871 --> 00:02:18,604
    so he whittles carefully,   

29
00:02:18,606 --> 00:02:22,508
   removing just a bit of wood  
 with each stroke of the knife. 

30
00:02:24,545 --> 00:02:26,345
            the goal            
   is to round the sharp edges  

31
00:02:26,347 --> 00:02:27,680
     and soften the profile     

32
00:02:27,682 --> 00:02:31,117
    without cutting too deep    
      and gouging the wood.     

33
00:02:33,287 --> 00:02:36,154
   he sands the entire surface  
          of the decoy          

34
00:02:36,156 --> 00:02:37,355
  until it's perfectly smooth.  

35
00:02:37,357 --> 00:02:40,626
      sanding also opens up     
      the pores of the wood     

36
00:02:40,628 --> 00:02:42,461
      so paint will adhere.     

37
00:02:46,100 --> 00:02:48,300
        he carves a mouth       

38
00:02:48,302 --> 00:02:51,904
       and then cuts slits      
   for two sets of side fins.   

39
00:02:54,642 --> 00:02:57,576
      using a power carver,     
   he now bores into the wood   

40
00:02:57,578 --> 00:03:01,380
   to create fish eye sockets   
         on both sides.         

41
00:03:02,917 --> 00:03:06,519
    he takes an equal amount    
  of two epoxy clay components  

42
00:03:06,521 --> 00:03:08,987
  and kneads the two together.  

43
00:03:08,989 --> 00:03:11,590
 this activates the ingredients,

44
00:03:11,592 --> 00:03:13,893
         turning it into        
     a putty-like adhesive.     

45
00:03:16,998 --> 00:03:18,931
 he presses some of the adhesive

46
00:03:18,933 --> 00:03:22,134
            into each           
   of the decoy's eye sockets.  

47
00:03:25,405 --> 00:03:29,809
    he presses the glass eyes   
 into the epoxy-filled sockets. 

48
00:03:35,349 --> 00:03:39,218
   next he cuts six fish fins   
   from a sheet of aluminum,    

49
00:03:39,220 --> 00:03:42,554
    creating one dorsal fin,    
     two sets of side fins,     

50
00:03:42,556 --> 00:03:44,857
      and a large tail fin.     

51
00:03:46,360 --> 00:03:50,296
       he inserts the fins      
   into slots in the carving.   

52
00:03:50,298 --> 00:03:53,398
      he then drills holes      
    in the wood on each side.   

53
00:03:53,400 --> 00:03:57,102
        he presses nails        
 into those holes using pliers. 

54
00:03:57,104 --> 00:03:59,672
   this secures the tail fin.   

55
00:04:01,375 --> 00:04:04,509
       the fins on decoys       
  are larger than on live fish  

56
00:04:04,511 --> 00:04:08,114
   to enable them to swim well  
         when weighted.         

57
00:04:08,116 --> 00:04:10,783
     he now carves a pocket     
       for the lead weight      

58
00:04:10,785 --> 00:04:12,952
       in the decoy belly.      

59
00:04:14,188 --> 00:04:16,589
 he inserts the front side fins,

60
00:04:16,591 --> 00:04:20,593
 so that they protrude slightly 
 into the freshly carved pocket.

61
00:04:20,595 --> 00:04:24,463
    he scoops up molten lead    
  and pours it into the pocket. 

62
00:04:24,465 --> 00:04:26,264
     as the lead solidifies,    

63
00:04:26,266 --> 00:04:29,268
      it weights the decoy      
        so it will sink,        

64
00:04:29,270 --> 00:04:32,137
       and it also secures      
       the two side fins.       

65
00:04:32,139 --> 00:04:34,272
  he applies epoxy to the lead, 

66
00:04:34,274 --> 00:04:37,742
    sealing it so it won't be   
      exposed to the water.     

67
00:04:37,744 --> 00:04:40,746
    he coats the entire decoy   
          with lacquer.         

68
00:04:40,748 --> 00:04:42,347
       this seals the wood      
         against water,         

69
00:04:42,349 --> 00:04:45,017
     which would have caused    
       the wood to swell,       

70
00:04:45,019 --> 00:04:46,885
   cracking the final finish.   

71
00:04:46,887 --> 00:04:48,887
     once the lacquer dries     

72
00:04:48,889 --> 00:04:51,223
     and the paint has been     
     scraped off the eyes,      

73
00:04:51,225 --> 00:04:54,093
       the decoy is ready       
       to take the plunge.      

74
00:04:54,095 --> 00:04:56,294
           he tests it          
    to confirm that it sinks    

75
00:04:56,296 --> 00:04:59,565
     and that it sits level     
     underwater and swims.      

76
00:04:59,567 --> 00:05:02,367
           sometimes,           
  more lead needs to be added.  

77
00:05:02,369 --> 00:05:07,039
   but in this case, the decoy  
    performs fine underwater.   

78
00:05:07,041 --> 00:05:11,243
 he marks a spot for a screw eye
   for threading fishing line   

79
00:05:11,245 --> 00:05:15,780
  and then twists the screw eye 
         into that spot.        

80
00:05:15,782 --> 00:05:18,984
   he paints the herring decoy  
         a vibrant red,         

81
00:05:18,986 --> 00:05:21,053
       a color that isn't       
    scientifically accurate,    

82
00:05:21,055 --> 00:05:23,789
      but one that should       
      tantalize real fish.      

83
00:05:23,791 --> 00:05:27,059
  decoys are often exact copies 
            of fish.            

84
00:05:27,061 --> 00:05:30,195
   they're designed to simply   
     pique their curiosity.     

85
00:05:30,197 --> 00:05:31,997
    since fish are attracted    

86
00:05:31,999 --> 00:05:35,000
      by colors and shapes      
    they don't normally see,    

87
00:05:35,002 --> 00:05:38,336
          decoy artists         
can be as creative as they like.

88
00:05:38,338 --> 00:05:40,405
 considered a form of folk art, 

89
00:05:40,407 --> 00:05:42,875
  fish decoys are often entered 
       into competitions.       

90
00:05:42,877 --> 00:05:46,879
   but of course when it comes  
   to their underwater allure,  

91
00:05:46,881 --> 00:05:48,547
  the real judges are the fish. 

