  and which frames are damaged, 

145
00:08:58,272 --> 00:09:02,407
 then they decided which version
  is in the best shape overall. 

146
00:09:02,409 --> 00:09:04,877
       that's the version       
         they digitize.         

147
00:09:04,879 --> 00:09:07,479
    later, they'll digitally    
  edit out the damaged portions 

148
00:09:07,481 --> 00:09:11,083
      and replace them with     
 identical but undamaged frames 

149
00:09:11,085 --> 00:09:13,018
  digitized from another copy.  

150
00:09:13,020 --> 00:09:14,686
    after threading the film    
      through the scanner,      

151
00:09:14,688 --> 00:09:16,154
       they close the gate      

152
00:09:16,156 --> 00:09:19,958
 to hold the film flat and close
     to the scanning camera.    

153
00:09:19,960 --> 00:09:23,295
   then they input the picture  
     quality specifications     

154
00:09:23,297 --> 00:09:24,596
        and start her up.       

155
00:09:26,167 --> 00:09:31,170
    the scanner gently loops    
  the film around its spools... 

156
00:09:35,176 --> 00:09:37,743
    ...and begins rolling it    
        past the camera.        

157
00:09:44,118 --> 00:09:46,718
 for the picture quality they've
 selected for this digitization,

158
00:09:46,720 --> 00:09:49,888
 the camera snaps three pictures
         of every frame.        

159
00:09:56,530 --> 00:09:57,863
  the scanner's control station 

160
00:09:57,865 --> 00:10:00,999
  displays what's being scanned 
          in real time,         

161
00:10:01,001 --> 00:10:03,268
           along with           
  all the technical parameters. 

162
00:10:03,270 --> 00:10:07,806
    this digitization process   
   itemizes every single frame  

163
00:10:07,808 --> 00:10:10,542
 so when they digitally replace 
        a damaged portion       

164
00:10:10,544 --> 00:10:12,811
      with an undamaged one     
        from another copy       

165
00:10:12,813 --> 00:10:16,115
  they can match everything up  
      to the exact frames.      

166
00:10:20,020 --> 00:10:22,220
         the final step         
      is color correction.      

167
00:10:22,222 --> 00:10:25,156
   because the digitized film   
